h3. Problem Definition
Currently, the developer.atlassian.com documentation regarding creating contents with the REST API ([this one|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/#api-api-content-post]) doesn't explain how to create pages on the new editor.

h3. Suggested Solution
Include the option to create pages on the new editor, as follows:
{code:none}"metadata": {
    "properties": {
        "editor": {
            "key": "editor",
            "value": "v2"
        }
    }
}{code}

h3. Issue Summary

Assuming that there is a hierarchy of custom contents
{code:java}
page:
- custom content parent (ac:app:parent)
  - custom content child (ac:app:child)
    - custom content grandchild (ac:app:child){code}
 grandchildren are not returned when calling a Get Content REST API with children expansion or Get Content Children By Type for the child custom content.
h3. Steps to Reproduce

Having the following custom content types configured (in {{atlassian-connect.json}})
{code:java}
"customContent": [
    {
        "key": "parent",
        "name": {
            "value": "Parent"
        },
        "apiSupport": {
           "supportedContainerTypes": [
               "page"
           ],
           "supportedChildTypes": [
               "ac:my-app:child"
           ],
           // ...
        }
    },
    {
        "key": "child",
        "name": {
            "value": "child"
        },
        "apiSupport": {
            "supportedContainerTypes": [
                "ac:my-app:parent",
                "ac:my-app:child"
            ],
            "supportedChildTypes": [
                "ac:my-app:child"
            ],
            // ...
        }
    }
]
{code}
 # Create a hierarchy of custom content as shown in issue summary. It can be done through a Create Content REST API (POST to rest/api/content) using the following request bodies. You have to use undocumented {{container}} parameter to specify a container page for parent custom content, container parent custom content for child custom component and so on.
{code:java}
{
    "type": "ac:my-app:parent",
    "title": "Custom Component Parent",
    "container": {
        "type": "page"
        "id": "<page-id>"
    },
    "space":{
        "key": "MYSPACEKEY"
    },
    "body":{
        "storage": {
            "value": "Custom Component Parent body",
            "representation": "storage"
        }
    }
}
{code}
{code:java}
{
    "type": "ac:my-app:child",
    "title": "Custom Component Child",
    "container": {
        "type": "ac:my-app:parent"
        "id": "<parent-custom-content-id>"
    },
    "space":{
        "key": "MYSPACEKEY"
    },
    "body":{
        "storage": {
            "value": "Custom Component Child body",
            "representation": "storage"
        }
    }
}{code}

 # Use GET request to Get Content (with expand) and Get Content Children By Type REST APIs to get a list of grandchildren
{code:java}
{{baseurl}}/rest/api/content/<child-id>?expand=children.ac__my_app__child{code}
{code:java}
{{baseurl}}/rest/api/content/<child-id>/child/ac:my-app:child{code}

h3. Expected Results

Both APIs return a list of grandchildren.
h3. Actual Results

The returned list is empty
h3. Workaround

Look up grandchild content id in the CONTENT table in the database
{code:java}
select contentid, title from content where contenttype = 'CUSTOM' and pageid = '<child-id>';
{code}
Get the returned content id and use Get Content REST API to get the grandchild content
{code:java}
{{baseurl}}/rest/api/content/<grandchildchild-id>
{code}

Existing REST API public documentation ([https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/#api-api-content-post]) is missing a {{container}} body parameter which is required in many cases.

For example trying to create a comment specifying a parent page in the {{ancestors}} field
{code:java}
{
    "type": "comment",
    "title": "Comment 1",
    "ancestors": [{
        "id": "3571724"
    }],
    "space":{
        "key": "MYSPACE"
    },
    "body":{
        "storage": {
            "value": "Comment 1 body",
            "representation": "storage"
        }
    }
}{code}
results to the error
{code:java}
"The container property is required when creating a Comment, and it must be another Content object"
{code}
However it's not described in the documentation.

 

Creation of a custom content, with an assumption that parent page should be specified in the {{ancestors}} field
{code:java}
{
    "type": "ac:my-awesome-app:component",
    "title": "Custom Component 1",
    "ancestors": [{
        "id": "3571724"
    }],
    "space":{
        "key": "CYBERDYNE"
    },
    "body":{
        "storage": {
            "value": "Custom Component 1 body",
            "representation": "storage"
        }
    }
}
{code}
results to the error 
{code:java}
"Content of type ac:my-awesome-app:component cannot be a child of space."
{code}
which doesn't give any pointers that user should specify a {{container}} field.

h3. Issue Summary
While using the *Children Display* macro and setting the _Excerpt Display field to +rich content+, the excerpted content doesn't load properly.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page called *Parent* and publish it;
# Create a page called *Child*;
# Add an *Excerpt* macro in this page;
# Insert a table within the macro and add some content, color, and formatting in the table;
# Publish the page;
# Edit *Parent* page;
# Insert the *Children Display* macro;
# In the *Excerpt Display* field, set it as _rich content_;
# Save it and publish the page.

h3. Expected Results
The excerpted content shows fine, as the original source (*Child* page).

h3. Actual Results
The content loads in the old editor style.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

When inserting a Roadmap Planner macro in a page that has a bodied macro before the roadmap (e.g.: Expand, Layout, iFrame), instead of the Roadmap be inserted in the place you defined, it is showing up inside the bodied macro. It is happening only when you edit the Roadmap properties like Bar name, Lane name, etc. It does not happen when you just change the size of bars, exclude bars or only insert the roadmap to the page.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Edit a Confluence page;
 # Select a place inside the page and type /roadmap and then, select the last option;
 # Edit the name for the bars, lanes, and all other options you need to edit there;
 # Click insert;

h3. Expected Results

The macro should be placed where you inserted it.
h3. Actual Results

The macro is being placed inside the last bodied macro on the page.
h3. Workaround

A possible workaround is:
 # Type /roadmap where you need to insert the macro;
 # On the macro editing box, just click on "Insert";
 # On the page editing mode, click on the macro and then, edit it as needed and insert it again.

h3. Problem Definition
Currently, on Confluence Cloud, admins are not able to disable collaborative editing on their instances.

h3. Suggested Solution
Grant site-admins the ability to toggle collaborative editing either on/off on:
* Instance level;
* Space level;
* Page level;


This could be useful for preventing multiple users from editing the page concurrently or prevent users from publishing the page while others are still editing;

h3. Issue Summary
Emojis from the new editor are being shown as a blue star when reported via "Page Properties Report" Macro on pages using the old editor

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Insert a page property macro in a page using the old editor (page #1);
# Create pages with the new edito using "Page Properties" macro in them;
# Inside this macro insert a a single line table and use any of the available emojis on the new editor (e.g. :left_right_arrow: or :up_arrow:);
 !Screen Shot 2020-03-13 at 15.55.28.png|thumbnail!  !Screen Shot 2020-03-13 at 15.55.21.png|thumbnail! 
# Go back to (page #1) and check the column containg the emoji be reported on this page;


h3. Expected Results
# Emoji to be correctly displayed on the old editor;

h3. Actual Results
# Emoji shown as a blue star

 !Screen Shot 2020-03-13 at 15.55.37.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Notes
* This affects both the old editor and the new one alike;
* This behavior also affects Page history

h3. Workaround
 Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary
Currently, on *Confluence Free* you're able to install Questions for Confluence, however due to the way permissions are restricted on this plan you'd be unable to answer questions and would be thrown an error:

{quote}Something went wrong
We're not sure what the problem is. Try again, and contact your admin if it still doesn't work.
{quote}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Navigate to [Try Confluence Page|https://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence/pricing] and choose a *Free License*;
 # After you chose this option you'll notice the page *Find New Apps* on the instance is not present;
 # Install a standard/Free Jira license on the instace;
 # Navigate to *Find New Apps* > Install Questions for Confluence;
 # Once the add-on is installed go ahead, ask a question;
 # Access the question to answer it

h3. Expected Results
 # You should be able to answer the question;

h3. Actual Results
 # Instead, the question is displayed and a generic error is thrown:
{quote}Something went wrong
We're not sure what the problem is. Try again, and contact your admin if it still doesn't work.
{quote}

h3. Workaround
 * The only available workaround is to convert the instance into a standard trial instance, by accessing *Manage subscriptions* and changing the subscription into *Standard*

h3. Issue Summary
Space Import will fail if Inline Tasks doesn't have a Creator assigned to them.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Export a Space from Confluence Server.
# Import the Space to Confluence Cloud.

h3. Expected Results
Space is imported successfully.

h3. Actual Results
Space import fails and the following error is thrown in the UI:
{code}
com.atlassian.confluence.importexport.ImportExportException: org.springframework.transaction.UnexpectedRollbackException: Transaction rolled back because it has been marked as rollback-only
{code}

h3. Diagnostic
Logs will look like below (Only Atlassian can see those):
{code}
Unable to publish track event: null value in entry: creator=null, safely handling it to not leak to upper layer!
{code}

This might happen if there's a Task Report Macro inside an Inline task as can be seen below:
!Screen Shot 2020-03-03 at 18.32.23.png|thumbnail!

What one could do is to get all pages with tasks that don't have an entry in the "AO_BAF3AA_AOINLINE_TASK" table, if that's the case then you will hit this bug:
{code:sql}
select c.contentid from content c, spaces s where c.spaceid = s.spaceid and c.contentid in 
(select contentid from bodycontent where body like '%ac:name="tasks-report-macro"%') 
and c.prevver is null and c.contentid not in (select "CONTENT_ID" from "AO_BAF3AA_AOINLINE_TASK")
and s.spacekey = '<SPACE_KEY_HERE>';
{code}

There's also a chance that this problem happens because of content missing a creation date in server. You can identify if your instance has content records on that state with the below query:
{code:sql}
select contentid,contenttype,content_status from content where creationdate is null and spaceid = (select spaceid from spaces where spacekey = '<SPACE_KEY_HERE>');
{code}

h3. Workaround
Then go to each page, delete the *Inline Task*, not the Task Report Macro and create the *Inline Task* again. To do so, pick each of the Content IDs retrieved from previous steps and use them in the following URL:
* _<Base-URL>/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=<ContentID>_

Once the task is recreated, you can use the ContentID to query the following table - It should return results now, whereas it wasn't earlier:
{code:sql}
select * from "AO_BAF3AA_AOINLINE_TASK" where "CONTENT_ID" = <ContentID>
{code}

With results returning in the above table, one would be safe to run a XML Export and then import it in Cloud.

If your issue is related to the missing creation date you should look to update those records directly in the database during a scheduled downtime.
To make this easier you can update all null records into a fixed date:
{code:sql}
update content set creationdate = '2018-06-11 10:00:00' where creationdate is null;
{code}

*Note*
If you don't know which space has caused the issue, you could run this query that will gather all pages in such state and thus potential candidates to be causing the problem:
{code}
select c.contentid, s.spacekey from content c, spaces s where c.spaceid = s.spaceid and c.contentid in 
(select contentid from bodycontent where body like '%ac:name="tasks-report-macro"%') 
and c.prevver is null and c.contentid not in (select "CONTENT_ID" from "AO_BAF3AA_AOINLINE_TASK");
{code}

h3. Issue Summary

Update  Atlassian Renderer Library to use HtmlSafeAnnotationBoxingUberspect. 

LIbrary: [https://bitbucket.org/atlassian/cloud-atlassian-template-renderer/src/master/]
h3. Steps to Reproduce

N/A
h3. Expected Results

Library should render only safe content
h3. Actual Results

The below exception is thrown in the xxxxxxx.log file:
{noformat}
...
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

Pass `runtimeConstants.UBERSPECT_CLASSNAME, ConfluenceAnnotationBoxingUberspect.class.getName())` in VelocityTemplateRendererImpl

Currently it is implemented as 

```

public class SecureVelocityTemplateRendererServiceFactory extends VelocityTemplateRendererServiceFactory{

private TemplateContextFactory templateContextFactory;
 public SecureVelocityTemplateRendererServiceFactory(TemplateContextFactory templateContextFactory)

{ super(templateContextFactory); this.templateContextFactory = templateContextFactory; }

@Override
 public VelocityTemplateRenderer getService(Bundle bundle, ServiceRegistration serviceRegistration)

{ String pluginKey = (String)bundle.getHeaders().get("Atlassian-Plugin-Key"); ClassLoader bundleClassLoader = BundleClassLoaderAccessor.getClassLoader(bundle); return new VelocityTemplateRendererImpl(bundleClassLoader, pluginKey, ImmutableMap.of(RuntimeConstants.UBERSPECT_CLASSNAME, ConfluenceAnnotationBoxingUberspect.class.getName()), this.templateContextFactory); }

}

``` in AtrAppConfig.java
